english:
  title: 'On the Distinction Between Mind and Traces: A Refutation of Buddhist Teaching'
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Mind is the master of the body, while traces are the manifestations of mind when it responds to things and encounters circumstances. Thus we say: where there is this mind, there must be these traces. They cannot be separated and made into two.

    The principles of the Four Sprouts, the Five Relationships, and all phenomena are wholly contained within this mind. When things present themselves in endless variation, this mind's principle responds to each stimulus appropriately, each in its proper place, without confusion or disorder. When one sees a child crawling toward a well, one is seized by alarm and compassion—this arises because that mind possesses the nature of benevolence. In seeing the child, what manifests outwardly is compassion. Can we truly say mind and traces are two separate things? The same holds for shame and aversion, deference and yielding, and right and wrong.

    Consider further what our body encounters: seeing a parent, we think of filial piety; seeing a child, we think of tenderness. We serve rulers with loyalty, direct ministers with propriety, and befriend others with trustworthiness. What causes this? It is because the mind possesses the natures of benevolence, righteousness, propriety, and wisdom. Thus what manifests outward reflects this inner reality. This is what is meant by substance and function arising from one source, with no gap between the manifest and the subtle.

    The Buddhist teaching takes only the mind and discards the traces. Thus they say: "Manjushri, the Great Sage, frequented taverns and wine shops. Though his traces were improper, his mind was correct." There are many such examples among them. Is this not a false separation of mind and traces?

    Master Cheng said: "In Buddhist learning, there is something of 'reverence to straighten the inner,' but there is nothing of 'righteousness to order the outer.' Therefore, the rigid become withered and hollow, while the loose become licentious and unrestrained. This is why the Buddhist teaching is so narrow. Yet without righteousness to order the outer, even the straightening of the inner cannot be right."

    Wang Tong, though a Confucian scholar, also said that mind and traces are divided. But this shows he was deluded by Buddhist ideas and did not understand. Therefore I set forth these arguments together.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Four Sprouts (四端) refer to the four incipient feelings—compassion, shame, respect, and right and wrong—foundational to Confucian virtue ethics as explained by Mencius.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Five Relationships (五典) refer to the five cardinal human relationships in Confucianism: ruler-subject, father-son, husband-wife, elder-younger brother, and friend-friend.'
  - key: ''
    value: Master Cheng refers to Cheng Yi (1033-1107), the Neo-Confucian philosopher whose critique of Buddhism influenced later Korean thinkers.
  - key: ''
    value: Wang Tong (王通, 584-617) was a pre-Tang Confucian scholar; the author criticizes him for compromising with Buddhist philosophy despite being nominally Confucian.
